s:1552:"<p dir="ltr" style="text-align:left;"><a>Spring Boot</a> Extension is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Framework" title="Spring Framework">Spring</a>'s <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convention_over_configuration" title="Convention over configuration">convention-over-configuration</a> solution for creating production-grade<sup><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Boot#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWalls2016vii%C2%A7foreword-2">[2]</a></sup> Spring applications with minimal amounts of configuration.<sup><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Boot#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWalls201637%E2%80%9348%C2%A72.3-3">[3]</a></sup> Most of the application can be preconfigured using Spring team's "opinionated view"<sup><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Boot#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWalls201648%C2%A72.4-4">[4]</a></sup><sup><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Boot#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDeinumCosmina202121%E2%80%9322%C2%A72_Spring_Framework_Fundamentals-5">[5]</a></sup> of the best configuration and use of the Spring platform and third-party libraries. A Spring Boot application can be written using several programming languages, including <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)">Java</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kotlin_(programming_language)" title="Kotlin (programming language)">Kotlin</a>.<sup><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Boot#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMusib20229%C2%A71.2.2_Java_vs_Kotlin-6">[6]</a></sup><br /></p>";